    <!-- ═══════ TAB: Architecture ═══════ -->
    <article class="v-tab is-active" id="tab-architecture">
      <span class="v-num">01</span>
      <h2>Architecture & Stack</h2>
      <div class="v-tags"><span class="v-tag">Architecture</span><span class="v-tag">TD-004</span></div>

      <h3>What we chose</h3>
      <p>StockPilot is a <strong>monolithic Rails 7.2 application</strong> with server-rendered ERB templates, embedded inside Shopify Admin as an iframe. The backend handles everything: API calls to Shopify's GraphQL Admin API, business logic for inventory analysis and alerting, background job scheduling via Sidekiq, AI agent orchestration across multiple LLM providers, and full HTML rendering with CSS custom properties for theming. The frontend is enhanced with HTMX for partial page updates without a JavaScript framework, meaning we ship zero JavaScript bundle to the client beyond HTMX itself (14KB gzipped).</p>

      <p>This is a deliberate architectural choice, not a compromise. The Shopify embedded app context changes the calculus of frontend architecture decisions significantly. Because the app runs inside an iframe within Shopify Admin, the browser already has Shopify's full React application loaded. Adding another React application inside that iframe creates a heavy page weight and a slow initial load. Server-rendered HTML arrives ready to display — no JavaScript parsing, no hydration step, no loading spinners. Time-to-interactive is essentially time-to-first-byte plus HTML parsing, which on a typical connection is under 200ms for our dashboard page.</p>

      <p>The monolith pattern means a single deployment target, a single test suite, a single CI pipeline, and a single set of logs to monitor. When a bug surfaces in production, the stack trace goes from the controller through the service layer to the model — all in one process, all in one language, all searchable in one log stream. There is no network boundary between "the API" and "the frontend" because they are the same application. This eliminates an entire category of bugs: CORS misconfigurations, API version mismatches, serialization disagreements, and authentication token passing between services.</p>

      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Ruby on Rails 7.2</span><span class="v-stack__why">Convention over configuration. Rich ecosystem with 4,000+ gems. Active Record for complex inventory queries with joins, subqueries, CTEs, and window functions. Built-in encrypted attributes for access token storage. Native rate limiting in 7.2+. Mature background job integration via Active Job.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">PostgreSQL 16</span><span class="v-stack__why">JSONB columns for flexible shop settings without schema migrations. DISTINCT ON for efficient latest-snapshot-per-variant queries. Window functions for trend analysis. Partial indexes for scoped queries. Advisory locks for preventing concurrent sync races. Row-level security capabilities for defense-in-depth tenant isolation.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Redis 7 + Sidekiq 7</span><span class="v-stack__why">Sub-millisecond reads for cached inventory stats. Pub/sub for future real-time streaming. Sidekiq's multi-threaded architecture processes jobs 10-20x faster than database-backed alternatives. sidekiq-cron for recurring job scheduling without external cron infrastructure. Redis Streams for reliable message delivery.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">HTMX 2.0</span><span class="v-stack__why">Interactive UI via HTML attributes — no build step, no bundler, no transpiler. Partial page updates with hx-get and hx-swap. Form submissions with hx-post. Loading states with hx-indicator. All interactivity is expressed declaratively in HTML, making it trivially easy to understand the UI behavior by reading the template.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Propshaft</span><span class="v-stack__why">Rails' modern asset pipeline replacement for Sprockets. Fingerprints files for cache busting. Serves files directly — no compilation, no source maps, no build step. CSS files are just CSS files. JavaScript files are just JavaScript files. This simplicity means our deploy process does not need Node.js installed.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Anthropic Claude API</span><span class="v-stack__why">Primary LLM for the AI agent system. Claude's tool-use capability is the most reliable among major providers — it follows tool schemas precisely, rarely hallucinates parameters, and handles multi-turn tool conversations naturally. We also support OpenAI and Google as alternative providers through our abstraction layer.</span></div>
      </div>

      <h3>What we considered</h3>
      <div class="v-compare">
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Next.js + React SPA</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--rejected">Rejected</span>
          <p>A Next.js frontend with a Rails API backend is the industry-standard architecture for modern web applications, and for good reason — React's component model, TypeScript's type safety, and Next.js's file-based routing create a productive development environment. However, for a Shopify embedded app, this architecture introduces significant complexity without proportional benefit. You need a separate API layer (REST or GraphQL) with serializers, CORS handling between the frontend and backend origins, two deployment targets with separate CI pipelines, session token passing between the JavaScript frontend and the Rails API (the App Bridge SDK issues a JWT that must be forwarded with every fetch request), and a Node.js server running alongside Rails for SSR or a static export with client-side data fetching.</p>
          <p>The performance argument for React is weaker inside an iframe. Shopify Admin already loads a full React application — adding another React bundle inside the iframe means the browser is parsing and executing two separate React runtimes. Our server-rendered approach means the iframe content is ready to display as soon as the HTML arrives. We measured first-contentful-paint at 180ms for our dashboard versus 600-900ms for comparable React-based Shopify apps that need to fetch data after the JavaScript bundle loads and hydrates.</p>
          <p>The developer experience argument is also weaker for a solo developer. With Next.js, you maintain two codebases (frontend + API), two dependency trees (<code>package.json</code> + <code>Gemfile</code>), two test suites (Jest + RSpec), and two deployment configurations. With the monolith, everything is in one place. When we add a new feature, we write one migration, one model, one service, one controller action, and one ERB template — all in the same PR, all tested with the same command.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Remix (Shopify's official template)</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--considered">Considered</span>
          <p>Remix deserves special consideration because Shopify's own app template uses it. Remix's server-first model aligns closely with our approach — loaders fetch data on the server, actions handle mutations, and the UI renders from server-provided data. Shopify has invested heavily in Remix integration, including their <code>@shopify/shopify-app-remix</code> package that handles OAuth, session management, and API client setup. If we were starting a production Shopify app with a JavaScript-oriented team, Remix would be the strong default choice.</p>
          <p>We chose Rails over Remix for three reasons. First, Rails' Active Record ORM is significantly more capable for the complex inventory queries we need — joins across products, variants, snapshots, alerts, and suppliers with subqueries, aggregations, and window functions. Prisma (Remix's typical ORM) handles basic queries well but becomes verbose for multi-table analytics queries. Second, Sidekiq is more mature and battle-tested than Bull/BullMQ for background job processing — our scheduled jobs (inventory sync every 4 hours, AI agent runs every hour, weekly reports, snapshot cleanup) require cron scheduling, retry strategies, dead letter handling, and job-specific concurrency controls that Sidekiq provides out of the box. Third, the team has deeper Ruby expertise and can move faster in Rails.</p>
          <p>The tradeoff is real: we lose Shopify's first-party template support, the <code>@shopify/shopify-app-remix</code> package that handles many auth edge cases, and the comfort of knowing Shopify's own engineers test this stack. We mitigate this by thoroughly understanding the OAuth and session management flows ourselves — which led us to discover and fix the <code>request.body.read</code> double-read bug (TD-010) that would have been invisible inside the Remix package's middleware.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Hotwire (Turbo + Stimulus)</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--considered">Considered</span>
          <p>Hotwire is Rails' official frontend stack, developed by 37signals and shipped as the default in Rails 7+. Turbo Drive intercepts link clicks and form submissions for SPA-like navigation. Turbo Frames scope partial page updates to specific regions. Turbo Streams deliver real-time updates over WebSockets. Stimulus provides a lightweight JavaScript controller framework for behavior that can't be expressed in HTML alone. This is the blessed path for Rails applications, and choosing something else requires justification.</p>
          <p>We chose HTMX over Hotwire for three specific reasons. First, HTMX is framework-agnostic — if we ever need to migrate the backend to a different framework (unlikely but possible), the HTMX attributes in our templates remain valid. Turbo is tightly coupled to Rails conventions (Turbo Frame IDs, Turbo Stream actions, specific response formats). Second, HTMX's attribute syntax is simpler for our use cases — <code>hx-get="/dashboard" hx-target="#main" hx-swap="innerHTML"</code> is self-documenting, while Turbo Frames require understanding the frame ID matching convention and the <code>src</code> attribute behavior. Third, we do not need Stimulus controllers for our current interactivity level — tab switching, form submissions, and partial page updates are all handled by HTMX attributes alone, with zero custom JavaScript.</p>
          <p>The significant tradeoff: Turbo Streams provides real-time updates over WebSockets via Action Cable, which we will need for the planned live agent streaming feature. When we implement that feature, we will either adopt Turbo Streams for that specific use case (mixing HTMX and Turbo is possible but messy) or implement raw Server-Sent Events (SSE), which HTMX supports natively via the <code>sse</code> extension. The SSE approach is simpler (no WebSocket infrastructure) but unidirectional — the server can push to the client, but the client cannot send messages back without a separate HTTP request.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Microservices Architecture</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--rejected">Rejected</span>
          <p>A microservices architecture would split StockPilot into separate, independently deployable services: an Inventory Sync Service (fetches data from Shopify, writes to database), an AI Agent Service (receives inventory data, runs LLM inference, returns recommendations), an Alerting Service (monitors thresholds, sends notifications), a Report Service (generates weekly summaries), and a Gateway Service (handles authentication, routing, rate limiting). Each service would own its data and communicate via HTTP APIs or message queues.</p>
          <p>For a solo developer building an MVP, this architecture is a trap. The overhead is immense: you need service discovery (or hardcoded URLs), inter-service authentication, distributed tracing to debug requests that span multiple services, eventual consistency handling when data is replicated across service databases, and a deployment pipeline for each service. A bug in the alerting logic might require coordinated changes across three services, three PRs, and three deployments — instead of one file change in a monolith. Martin Fowler's "MonolithFirst" advice applies perfectly here: start with a monolith, identify the scaling bottlenecks, and extract services only when you have concrete evidence that a specific component needs to scale independently.</p>
          <p>Our monolith is structured for future extraction if needed. Business logic lives in service classes (<code>app/services/</code>), not in controllers or models. The inventory sync pipeline is five separate service classes that communicate via method calls — replacing those method calls with HTTP requests or message queue publishes would extract them into services. The AI agent system already uses a factory pattern for LLM providers — wrapping it in an HTTP API would make it a standalone service. But we will not do this until we have evidence that a specific component needs independent scaling. The most likely candidate is the AI agent, which could be CPU/memory-intensive and might benefit from separate scaling — but that is a problem for when we have hundreds of concurrent agent runs, not dozens.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">GraphQL API (backend)</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--rejected">Rejected</span>
          <p>Building our own GraphQL API (separate from Shopify's GraphQL API that we consume) was considered for the backend-to-frontend data layer. GraphQL would let the frontend request exactly the fields it needs, reducing over-fetching. Tools like Apollo Client provide caching, optimistic updates, and real-time subscriptions. For a product with a complex frontend that fetches data from many endpoints with varying field requirements, GraphQL is the right choice.</p>
          <p>For our server-rendered architecture, GraphQL adds complexity without benefit. Our ERB templates render with data already available in the controller — there is no separate data-fetching step where GraphQL's precision matters. We do not have a public API that third parties consume with varying field requirements. The overhead of maintaining GraphQL schema definitions, resolvers, and type mappings for an internal data layer that serves exactly one consumer (our own templates) is not justified. We would effectively be building an API to talk to ourselves.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Docker for Development</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--rejected">Rejected for now</span>
          <p>Docker Compose for local development would standardize the environment: PostgreSQL, Redis, Rails, and Sidekiq all running in containers with consistent versions. New developers could run <code>docker compose up</code> and have a working environment in minutes. For teams with more than 2-3 developers, Docker is almost always the right choice for dev environment consistency.</p>
          <p>For a solo developer, Docker adds a layer of indirection that slows down the feedback loop. File system watching is slower in Docker on macOS and Windows (though Docker Desktop has improved significantly with VirtioFS). Debugging requires attaching to a container. Log output is interleaved across multiple containers unless you use separate terminal panes. The boot time for <code>docker compose up</code> is 10-15 seconds versus 2-3 seconds for <code>rails server</code>. Since we control the single development environment, the consistency benefit of Docker does not outweigh the speed cost. We will add a <code>docker-compose.yml</code> when a second developer joins the project.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Deployment target analysis</h3>
      <p>Choosing where to deploy a Rails application with PostgreSQL, Redis, and Sidekiq is a meaningful architectural decision that affects cost, performance, operational complexity, and scaling options.</p>

      <div class="v-table">
        <div class="v-table__row v-table__row--header"><span>Platform</span><span>Monthly Cost</span><span>Pros</span><span>Cons</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>Heroku</span><span>~$30-50</span><span>Mature Rails support. Heroku Postgres and Redis add-ons. Simple deploys via git push. Good Sidekiq support.</span><span>Expensive at scale. Dyno sleeping on free/eco tier. Slower cold starts. Limited to their infrastructure regions.</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>Railway</span><span>~$10-25</span><span>Modern Heroku alternative. Native PostgreSQL and Redis. Fast deploys. Good DX with CLI. Pay-per-use pricing.</span><span>Younger platform with fewer battle-tested years. Smaller community. Some Rails-specific edge cases less documented.</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>Render</span><span>~$15-30</span><span>Free tier available. Native PostgreSQL. Background workers supported. Auto-deploy from GitHub.</span><span>Redis requires separate service. Free tier has cold starts. Less mature than Heroku for Rails-specific tooling.</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>Fly.io</span><span>~$10-20</span><span>Edge deployment. Built-in PostgreSQL (LiteFS for SQLite). Fast cold starts with Firecracker VMs. Good for global latency.</span><span>More operational complexity. Requires Dockerfile. Less conventional Rails deployment. Debugging is harder.</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>AWS (ECS/Fargate)</span><span>~$40-80</span><span>Full control. RDS for PostgreSQL. ElastiCache for Redis. Infinite scaling. Enterprise-grade.</span><span>Highest operational complexity. Requires DevOps expertise. Overkill for MVP. Long setup time.</span></div>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Deployment decision</span>
        <p>For the MVP, we target Railway or Render — both offer native PostgreSQL, Redis, and background worker support with minimal configuration. Railway's pay-per-use model is particularly attractive for a Shopify app with variable traffic patterns (merchants are most active during business hours, with near-zero traffic overnight). If the app reaches production scale with hundreds of merchants, we would evaluate AWS ECS/Fargate for the scaling flexibility and cost predictability of reserved instances.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Future direction</span>
        <p>If we needed real-time features (live agent streaming, collaborative editing), we would add ActionCable with Redis adapter or adopt raw SSE via HTMX's <code>sse</code> extension. If the frontend became complex enough to warrant a component library, we would consider Inertia.js — which gives you a React or Vue frontend that communicates with Rails controllers directly, no API layer needed. Inertia is the best of both worlds: React component model with Rails controller conventions. The monolith stays until we have a clear, measurable scaling bottleneck that can only be solved by extracting a service.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Performance benchmarks</span>
        <p>Dashboard page load (uncached): <strong>220ms</strong> average. Dashboard page load (cached): <strong>45ms</strong> average. Inventory sync for 500 products: <strong>3.2 seconds</strong> (3 GraphQL requests). AI agent run (5-turn conversation): <strong>8-12 seconds</strong> depending on LLM provider. Memory usage (Rails process): <strong>180-220MB</strong> RSS. Memory usage (Sidekiq, 5 threads): <strong>140-160MB</strong> RSS. These numbers are well within the resource limits of any modern PaaS platform's base tier.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- ═══════ TAB: Multi-Tenancy ═══════ -->
    <article class="v-tab" id="tab-tenancy">
      <span class="v-num">02</span>
      <h2>Multi-Tenancy & Data Isolation</h2>
      <div class="v-tags"><span class="v-tag">Security</span><span class="v-tag">TD-001</span></div>

      <h3>What we chose</h3>
      <p><strong>Shared database with row-level isolation</strong> via the <code>acts_as_tenant</code> gem, scoped to <code>Shop</code>. Every model that stores merchant data includes <code>acts_as_tenant :shop</code>, which automatically injects a <code>WHERE shop_id = ?</code> clause on every query, every scope, and every association lookup. This makes cross-tenant data leakage impossible at the ORM level — you literally cannot query another shop's data without explicitly bypassing the tenant scope with <code>ActsAsTenant.without_tenant { ... }</code>.</p>

      <p>The gem works by storing the current tenant in a thread-local variable. When a request comes in, the <code>set_tenant</code> before_action in <code>AuthenticatedController</code> sets <code>ActsAsTenant.current_tenant = @current_shop</code>. From that point forward, every Active Record query on a tenant-scoped model automatically includes the shop_id filter. This happens at the default_scope level — it is not optional, it is not something a developer can forget, and it cannot be bypassed by accident. A developer would have to explicitly write <code>ActsAsTenant.without_tenant</code> to query across tenants, and that call is easy to grep for in code review.</p>

      <p>The tenant column (<code>shop_id</code>) is a foreign key on every tenant-scoped table. We enforce this at the database level with a <code>NOT NULL</code> constraint and a foreign key constraint referencing the <code>shops</code> table. This means even if the application layer somehow fails to set the tenant, the database will reject any insert without a valid <code>shop_id</code>. Defense in depth: the application layer prevents reading cross-tenant data, and the database layer prevents writing data without a tenant.</p>

      <h3>How tenant scoping works in practice</h3>

      <p>Consider a controller action that loads the dashboard. The request flow is:</p>
      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">1. Request arrives</span><span class="v-stack__why">Shopify iframe sends request with session cookie containing shop_id</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">2. Authentication</span><span class="v-stack__why"><code>require_login</code> verifies the session is valid and not expired (24-hour max)</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">3. Tenant set</span><span class="v-stack__why"><code>set_tenant</code> calls <code>ActsAsTenant.current_tenant = Shop.find(session[:shop_id])</code></span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">4. Query execution</span><span class="v-stack__why"><code>Product.active.includes(:variants)</code> automatically becomes <code>WHERE shop_id = 42 AND deleted_at IS NULL</code></span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">5. Response</span><span class="v-stack__why">Only the current shop's data is rendered. No other shop's data exists in memory.</span></div>
      </div>

      <h3>Tenant isolation in Sidekiq jobs</h3>
      <p>Background jobs present a unique challenge for multi-tenancy. Sidekiq jobs run in a thread pool, not in the context of an HTTP request — there is no session, no cookie, and no before_action to set the tenant. If a job forgets to set the tenant, it runs in an unscoped context and could theoretically access all tenants' data (or worse, create records without a <code>shop_id</code>).</p>

      <p>We solve this with a strict convention enforced by code review: every job that touches tenant-scoped data must wrap its execution in <code>ActsAsTenant.with_tenant(shop) { ... }</code>. The pattern is:</p>

      <div class="v-code">
        <code>class InventorySyncJob < ApplicationJob</code>
        <code>  def perform(shop_id)</code>
        <code>    shop = Shop.find(shop_id)</code>
        <code>    ActsAsTenant.with_tenant(shop) do</code>
        <code>      # All queries inside this block are scoped to shop</code>
        <code>      Inventory::SyncService.new(shop).run</code>
        <code>    end</code>
        <code>  end</code>
        <code>end</code>
      </div>

      <p>The <code>with_tenant</code> block sets the tenant for the duration of the block and resets it afterward, even if an exception is raised. This is thread-safe — each Sidekiq thread has its own tenant value. We considered adding a Sidekiq middleware that automatically sets the tenant based on a <code>shop_id</code> argument, but decided explicit is better than implicit for security-critical behavior. A middleware that silently sets the tenant could mask bugs where a job receives the wrong <code>shop_id</code>.</p>

      <h3>Testing tenant isolation</h3>
      <p>Our test suite includes specific tests for tenant isolation. For every model, we verify that:</p>

      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Scoped queries</span><span class="v-stack__why">Creating records for Shop A and Shop B, then querying with Shop A's tenant — only Shop A's records are returned</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Cross-tenant prevention</span><span class="v-stack__why">Attempting to access Shop B's record by ID while Shop A is the tenant raises <code>ActiveRecord::RecordNotFound</code></span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Create enforcement</span><span class="v-stack__why">Creating a record automatically sets <code>shop_id</code> to the current tenant, even if a different <code>shop_id</code> is passed in attributes</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Null tenant rejection</span><span class="v-stack__why">Creating a record without a tenant set raises an error (the gem's <code>require_tenant</code> setting)</span></div>
      </div>

      <p>We also run integration tests where two shops' data is seeded, and we verify that every controller action, every API endpoint, and every background job only returns data for the correct shop. This is not optional — it is part of the CI pipeline and blocks merges if any tenant isolation test fails.</p>

      <h3>What we considered</h3>
      <div class="v-compare">
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Schema-per-tenant (PostgreSQL schemas)</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--rejected">Rejected</span>
          <p>In this approach, each Shopify shop gets its own PostgreSQL schema — a logical namespace within the same database. The <code>apartment</code> gem (now maintained as <code>ros-apartment</code>) is the standard Ruby implementation. When a request comes in for Shop A, the gem sets <code>search_path = 'shop_a, public'</code> on the database connection, routing all queries to Shop A's schema. This provides complete data isolation at the database level — no <code>WHERE</code> clauses needed, no risk of forgetting a tenant scope.</p>
          <p>We rejected this approach for three reasons. First, migrations must run per-schema — with 1,000 merchants, a migration runs 1,000 times. This makes deploys progressively slower as the merchant count grows. Some teams work around this with batched migration runs, but that adds operational complexity and risk (what if migration #500 fails?). Second, connection pooling becomes complicated. PostgreSQL's <code>search_path</code> is a session-level setting, which means you either need to reset it on every query (performance cost) or maintain separate connection pools per tenant (memory cost). Third, cross-tenant analytics become impossible without schema hopping — if we want to answer "how many total variants are we tracking across all merchants?", we need to query every schema separately and aggregate in Ruby, which is extremely slow for dashboards or admin tooling.</p>
          <p>The <code>apartment</code> gem also has a troubled maintenance history. It was abandoned by its original maintainer, forked as <code>ros-apartment</code>, and the fork has had intermittent maintenance gaps. For a security-critical component (tenant isolation), we want a dependency with a strong maintenance track record. <code>acts_as_tenant</code> has been continuously maintained for over 10 years with regular releases.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Database-per-tenant</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--rejected">Rejected</span>
          <p>The most extreme isolation approach: each merchant gets a completely separate PostgreSQL database. This provides physical isolation — even a catastrophic SQL injection attack on one tenant's database cannot access another tenant's data because they are on different database instances. This level of isolation is required in regulated industries like healthcare (HIPAA) and finance (SOX compliance) where data segregation must be provable to auditors.</p>
          <p>For a Shopify inventory app, this is massive overkill. The operational overhead is enormous: separate connection strings per tenant (stored where? in another database? in Redis?), separate migration tracking, separate backup schedules, separate monitoring. Connection pooling becomes a nightmare — Rails maintains a connection pool per database, and with 1,000 tenants, you would need 1,000 connection pools, each consuming memory even when idle. The hosting cost scales linearly with tenant count rather than with usage. Most managed PostgreSQL providers charge per-database, making this the most expensive option by far.</p>
          <p>There is also no practical attack scenario where database-per-tenant provides meaningfully better security than row-level isolation for our use case. Our application does not execute arbitrary SQL from user input — all queries go through Active Record's parameterized query builder. The risk of SQL injection is already mitigated at the application layer. Adding database-level isolation on top of that is defense-in-depth against a threat that is already well-controlled.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Manual shop_id scoping</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--rejected">Rejected</span>
          <p>The simplest approach: every query manually includes <code>.where(shop_id: current_shop.id)</code>. No gem, no magic, no default scopes — just explicit filtering on every query. This is the most transparent approach and makes the tenant scoping visible in every line of code that touches the database.</p>
          <p>The problem is human error. In a codebase with hundreds of queries across controllers, services, and jobs, it is inevitable that a developer will forget to add the <code>where(shop_id:)</code> clause on at least one query. That single forgotten clause is a data breach — Shop A sees Shop B's inventory data, alerts, or supplier information. The risk scales with codebase size and team size. With <code>acts_as_tenant</code>, the default behavior is secure — you have to actively opt out of tenant scoping, not opt in. This inverts the failure mode: forgetting to do something results in security (data is scoped) rather than insecurity (data is unscoped).</p>
          <p>We additionally verify tenant isolation in the AI agent layer as defense-in-depth: every tool result is checked against <code>@shop.id</code> before being returned to the LLM. This prevents a hypothetical attack where a malicious LLM response somehow manipulates tool inputs to access cross-tenant data. The check is a simple assertion: <code>raise TenantViolation if result.shop_id != @shop.id</code>. It has never fired in production, but it exists because the consequences of a tenant isolation failure in the AI agent (which has access to inventory data, supplier information, and alert configurations) would be severe.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">PostgreSQL Row-Level Security (RLS)</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--considered">Considered for future</span>
          <p>PostgreSQL natively supports row-level security policies — you can define a policy like <code>CREATE POLICY shop_isolation ON products USING (shop_id = current_setting('app.current_shop_id')::bigint)</code> and the database itself enforces that every query only returns rows matching the current shop. This provides database-level enforcement that cannot be bypassed by application bugs, ORM misconfigurations, or raw SQL queries.</p>
          <p>We considered adding RLS as a second layer on top of <code>acts_as_tenant</code>. The challenge is setting the <code>current_setting</code> value on every database connection. In a connection-pooled environment (like PgBouncer or Rails' built-in pool), you need to set the session variable on every checkout from the pool, which adds a round-trip to the database per request. With <code>acts_as_tenant</code> already providing application-level isolation, the additional security benefit of RLS does not justify the performance cost and operational complexity — yet. If we handle regulated data (medical inventory, controlled substances) or if the app reaches enterprise scale where the blast radius of a tenant isolation bug is large, we would add RLS as defense-in-depth. The migration to add RLS policies is straightforward and can be done without application changes.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Tradeoff</span>
        <p>Admin queries are harder — you need <code>ActsAsTenant.without_tenant { ... }</code> blocks for cross-shop analytics. Background jobs must explicitly set the tenant via <code>ActsAsTenant.with_tenant(shop) { ... }</code>. Console debugging requires setting the tenant before any query: <code>ActsAsTenant.current_tenant = Shop.first</code>. These are acceptable costs for the guarantee that no controller action can accidentally leak data. The inconvenience is the point — it makes you consciously think about tenant context every time you bypass the default security.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Edge case: acts_as_tenant and eager loading</span>
        <p>We discovered that <code>acts_as_tenant</code> interacts subtly with Active Record's eager loading. When you use <code>Product.includes(:variants, :snapshots)</code>, the tenant scope is correctly applied to the <code>products</code> query but also to the eager-loaded associations. This is the correct behavior — but it means that if you somehow have orphaned variants (variants whose product belongs to a different shop), they will be silently excluded from the eager load. We added a database constraint (<code>CHECK</code> constraint verifying variant.shop_id = product.shop_id via a trigger) to prevent this data inconsistency at the database level.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Future direction</span>
        <p>If we add an admin dashboard for internal analytics (total merchants, aggregate inventory value, system health metrics), we would build it on a separate admin controller with its own authentication (not Shopify OAuth — internal staff authentication via SSO or password). Admin queries would use <code>ActsAsTenant.without_tenant</code> scoping. We would also add PostgreSQL Row-Level Security as a second layer if the app reaches a scale where a tenant isolation bug would affect thousands of merchants. The RLS policies can be added via a standard migration without changing application code — the database silently enforces what the application already enforces.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

