    <article class="v-tab" id="tab-auth">
      <span class="v-num">03</span>
      <h2>Authentication & OAuth</h2>
      <div class="v-tags"><span class="v-tag">Auth</span><span class="v-tag">TD-005</span><span class="v-tag">TD-006</span></div>

      <h3>What we chose</h3>
      <p><strong>Custom OAuth 2.0 implementation via OmniAuth</strong> with the <code>omniauth-shopify-oauth2</code> strategy. We handle the full OAuth authorization code flow ourselves: redirect to Shopify's authorization endpoint, receive the callback with an authorization code, exchange it for an access token, encrypt and store the token, and establish a server-side session. Access tokens are encrypted at rest using Rails 7.2's <code>encrypts :access_token</code> with deterministic encryption (allowing lookups by encrypted value). Sessions use Rails' cookie store with 24-hour expiry and <code>SameSite=None; Secure</code> attributes required for iframe embedding.</p>

      <h3>The OAuth 2.0 flow in detail</h3>
      <p>Understanding the complete OAuth flow is essential because every step has security implications. Here is the exact sequence of events when a merchant installs StockPilot:</p>

      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">1. Merchant clicks "Add app"</span><span class="v-stack__why">Shopify redirects to our <code>/auth/shopify</code> endpoint with <code>shop</code>, <code>timestamp</code>, and <code>hmac</code> query parameters</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">2. HMAC verification</span><span class="v-stack__why">We verify the HMAC-SHA256 signature using our API secret to confirm the request came from Shopify, not an attacker</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">3. OmniAuth redirect</span><span class="v-stack__why">OmniAuth constructs the authorization URL with our API key, requested scopes (<code>read_products,read_inventory,read_orders,read_customers</code>), redirect URI, and a <code>state</code> parameter (CSRF nonce)</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">4. Merchant authorizes</span><span class="v-stack__why">Shopify shows the permission consent screen. Merchant clicks "Install app". Shopify redirects back to our <code>/auth/shopify/callback</code> with an authorization code and the state parameter</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">5. State verification</span><span class="v-stack__why">OmniAuth verifies the <code>state</code> parameter matches the nonce we sent — this prevents CSRF attacks where an attacker tricks a merchant into authorizing with the attacker's account</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">6. Token exchange</span><span class="v-stack__why">We POST to <code>https://{shop}.myshopify.com/admin/oauth/access_token</code> with the authorization code, API key, and API secret. Shopify returns a permanent access token</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">7. Token storage</span><span class="v-stack__why">We encrypt the access token using Rails' <code>encrypts</code> and store it in the <code>shops</code> table. The encryption key is derived from <code>RAILS_MASTER_KEY</code></span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">8. Session creation</span><span class="v-stack__why">We create a server-side session with <code>session[:shop_id] = shop.id</code> and set the tenant for the duration of the request</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">9. Redirect to app</span><span class="v-stack__why">The merchant is redirected to the dashboard, now fully authenticated and authorized with their shop's data scoped via <code>acts_as_tenant</code></span></div>
      </div>

      <h3>Token encryption details</h3>
      <p>Shopify access tokens are permanent (they do not expire) and grant full read access to the shop's data within our requested scopes. If an attacker obtains a plaintext access token from our database, they can read the merchant's products, inventory, orders, and customer data directly via Shopify's API — without going through our application at all. This makes token encryption critical, not optional.</p>

      <p>Rails 7.2's <code>encrypts</code> uses AES-256-GCM by default, with the encryption key derived from the application's master key (<code>RAILS_MASTER_KEY</code> environment variable). We use deterministic encryption (not the default random encryption) so that we can look up a shop by its encrypted access token if needed — this is a tradeoff between security (random encryption is more resistant to frequency analysis) and functionality (deterministic allows database lookups). For our use case, frequency analysis is not a practical attack vector because each shop has a unique token.</p>

      <h3>Session security in iframes</h3>
      <p>Shopify embedded apps run inside an iframe within Shopify Admin. This creates a specific challenge for cookie-based sessions: modern browsers increasingly block third-party cookies (cookies set by a domain different from the top-level page). Since our app's domain is different from <code>admin.shopify.com</code>, our session cookies are technically third-party cookies.</p>

      <p>We mitigate this with:</p>
      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">SameSite=None</span><span class="v-stack__why">Required for cookies to be sent in cross-origin iframe requests. Without this, Chrome blocks the cookie entirely.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Secure flag</span><span class="v-stack__why">Required when SameSite=None. Ensures the cookie is only sent over HTTPS.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">24-hour expiry</span><span class="v-stack__why">Sessions expire after 24 hours. The merchant must re-authenticate via OAuth on the next visit after expiry.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">HttpOnly flag</span><span class="v-stack__why">The session cookie is not accessible to JavaScript, preventing XSS-based session theft.</span></div>
      </div>

      <h3>What we considered</h3>
      <div class="v-compare">
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">shopify_app gem (full-stack auth)</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--rejected">Rejected for MVP</span>
          <p>Shopify's official <code>shopify_app</code> gem is the blessed path for Rails-based Shopify apps. It bundles OAuth flow management (including online vs. offline tokens), session management with configurable storage backends (Active Record, Redis, or custom), automatic App Bridge integration for iframe embedding, webhook registration and verification, and API client configuration. The gem handles dozens of edge cases that are easy to miss in a custom implementation: token refresh for online tokens, session replay protection, handling the <code>shop</code> parameter across redirects, and iframe breakout detection.</p>
          <p>We chose to implement authentication ourselves for two reasons. First, as a portfolio project, understanding every line of the auth flow is more valuable than abstracting it away. We found and fixed the <code>request.body.read</code> double-read bug (TD-010) because we wrote the webhook verification code ourselves — inside the gem's middleware stack, this bug would have been invisible. Second, the gem couples you to their session storage strategy and makes it harder to customize session behavior (like our custom 24-hour expiry with shop-specific timezone-aware handling). The gem's conventions are well-designed, but when you need to deviate from them, you end up fighting the abstraction rather than working with it.</p>
          <p>The tradeoff is significant: we maintain more code, we risk missing edge cases the gem handles, and we do not get automatic updates when Shopify changes their auth requirements. For a production app targeting the Shopify App Store, we would seriously reconsider this decision and likely adopt the gem, using our custom code as a reference to understand what the gem does internally.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">App Bridge Session Tokens (JWT)</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--planned">Planned for v2</span>
          <p>Shopify's recommended authentication mechanism for embedded apps is session tokens, not cookies. The Shopify App Bridge JavaScript SDK generates a JWT (JSON Web Token) signed by Shopify on the client side. Every request from the frontend to your backend includes this JWT in the <code>Authorization</code> header. The backend verifies the JWT signature using Shopify's public key, extracts the <code>dest</code> (shop domain) and <code>sub</code> (user ID) claims, and uses them to identify the shop and user — no cookies needed.</p>
          <p>This approach solves the third-party cookie problem entirely: since authentication is via HTTP headers, not cookies, browser cookie policies are irrelevant. It also provides stronger CSRF protection — the JWT must be explicitly attached to each request by JavaScript, so cross-origin requests cannot forge authentication. The JWT has a short expiry (typically 1 minute), so even if intercepted, the window of exploitation is narrow. Shopify requires session token authentication for all new app submissions to the App Store.</p>
          <p>We have not implemented this yet because it requires the App Bridge JavaScript SDK on the frontend, which adds a JavaScript dependency to our otherwise JavaScript-minimal architecture. The implementation plan is: (1) add the App Bridge SDK via CDN, (2) write a small JavaScript module that fetches a session token and attaches it to HTMX requests via the <code>hx-headers</code> attribute, (3) add a <code>verify_session_token</code> before_action that decodes and verifies the JWT on every request, (4) remove the cookie-based session entirely. This is a prerequisite for Shopify App Store submission and is the highest-priority technical debt item.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Devise</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--rejected">Rejected</span>
          <p>Devise is Ruby's most popular authentication library, used by thousands of Rails applications. It provides a complete user authentication system: registration, login, password hashing (bcrypt), email confirmation, password reset, account locking, session management, and "remember me" tokens. It is the right choice for any application where users create accounts with email and password.</p>
          <p>Shopify apps do not have user accounts. Merchants authenticate via Shopify's OAuth flow — there is no email, no password, no registration form. The "user" is the shop itself, identified by its Shopify domain. Adding Devise would introduce an entire authentication subsystem (password hashing, confirmation emails, password resets, account lockouts) that has no use case in our application. It would also create confusion about what "authentication" means — are we authenticating the Shopify OAuth flow or the Devise user model? For Shopify apps, OAuth is the only authentication mechanism.</p>
          <p>The one scenario where Devise might make sense is if we add a separate admin dashboard for internal staff (not merchants). In that case, we would use Devise for admin authentication alongside Shopify OAuth for merchant authentication. But even then, we would likely use a simpler solution like <code>has_secure_password</code> with a custom admin model rather than Devise's full framework.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange)</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--considered">Considered</span>
          <p>PKCE is an extension to the OAuth 2.0 authorization code flow designed to prevent authorization code interception attacks. Instead of relying solely on the client secret to exchange the authorization code for a token, the client generates a random <code>code_verifier</code>, hashes it to create a <code>code_challenge</code>, sends the challenge in the authorization request, and sends the verifier in the token exchange request. This proves that the same client that initiated the flow is completing it, even if the authorization code is intercepted.</p>
          <p>PKCE was designed for public clients (mobile apps, SPAs) that cannot securely store a client secret. Our application is a confidential client — the client secret is stored server-side in an environment variable and never exposed to the browser. For confidential clients, the standard authorization code flow with client secret is sufficient. Shopify's OAuth implementation does not require PKCE for server-side apps, though they support it. We would add PKCE if Shopify makes it mandatory in a future API version, but the security benefit for our architecture (server-side, confidential client) is marginal.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Online vs. Offline access tokens</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--chose-offline">Chose offline tokens</span>
          <p>Shopify offers two types of access tokens. Online tokens are tied to a specific staff member's session — they expire when the staff member logs out or after 24 hours. Offline tokens are tied to the app installation itself — they do not expire and remain valid until the merchant uninstalls the app. Online tokens are more secure (shorter-lived, scoped to a specific user) but cannot be used for background processing (they expire, and there is no user session in a Sidekiq job).</p>
          <p>We use offline tokens because our background jobs (inventory sync, AI agent runs, weekly reports) need to call Shopify's API without an active user session. A job that runs at 3 AM cannot prompt a staff member to re-authenticate. The tradeoff is that offline tokens are a higher-value target for attackers — a stolen offline token provides permanent access to the shop's data until the merchant revokes it. We mitigate this with encryption at rest, never logging tokens, and strict parameter filtering. If we add features that require user-specific authorization (like tracking which staff member approved a purchase order), we would add online tokens alongside offline tokens.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Critical bug found (TD-010)</span>
        <p>Webhook and GDPR controllers called <code>request.body.read</code> twice — once for HMAC-SHA256 verification (computing the signature of the raw request body), and once for JSON parsing (extracting the webhook payload). The request body in Rack is an <code>IO</code> stream; reading it twice returns an empty string the second time because the stream position is at the end. This meant <strong>all webhook product updates were silently failing</strong> with empty payloads — the HMAC verification succeeded (it read the body correctly), but the JSON parsing received an empty string and raised no error (an empty string parsed as JSON is <code>nil</code>, which our code handled as "no data"). The fix was memoizing the body: <code>@webhook_body ||= request.body.read</code>. Both the HMAC verification and JSON parsing now use the same memoized string. This bug would have been invisible inside the <code>shopify_app</code> gem because the gem's middleware reads the body once and passes it through the middleware chain.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Scaling concern: session storage</span>
        <p>We currently use Rails' cookie store for sessions, which means the session data is stored in the cookie itself (encrypted with the master key). This works for small session payloads (just <code>shop_id</code> and <code>created_at</code>), but cookies have a 4KB size limit. If we need to store more session data in the future (user preferences, feature flags, multi-step wizard state), we would switch to Redis-backed sessions via <code>redis-session-store</code>. This also enables server-side session revocation — with cookie store, you cannot invalidate a session without changing the master key (which invalidates all sessions).</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Future direction: App Bridge lifecycle</span>
        <p>When we migrate to App Bridge session tokens, the authentication lifecycle changes fundamentally. App Bridge initializes on page load and immediately provides a session token. Our HTMX requests will include this token via a custom header. The backend will verify the token's JWT signature, check the <code>iss</code> (issuer) and <code>dest</code> (destination shop) claims, extract the shop domain, and look up the shop record. This eliminates cookies entirely and solves the third-party cookie problem that is increasingly blocking embedded apps in Safari and Firefox. The migration path is well-defined and is the single most important technical debt item before App Store submission.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

