    <article class="v-tab" id="tab-database">
      <span class="v-num">11</span>
      <h2>Database Design</h2>
      <div class="v-tags"><span class="v-tag">PostgreSQL</span><span class="v-tag">TD-008</span><span class="v-tag">TD-009</span></div>

      <h3>Schema overview</h3>
      <p>The database schema is designed around the core entities of inventory management: shops, products, variants, inventory snapshots, alerts, suppliers, purchase orders, and audit logs. Every table (except <code>shops</code> itself) includes a <code>shop_id</code> foreign key for multi-tenancy. The schema uses PostgreSQL-specific features (JSONB, DISTINCT ON, partial indexes, advisory locks) that would not be portable to MySQL — this is a deliberate tradeoff in favor of PostgreSQL's superior capabilities for our use case.</p>

      <div class="v-table">
        <div class="v-table__row v-table__row--header"><span>Table</span><span>Rows (typical shop)</span><span>Growth rate</span><span>Key indexes</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>shops</span><span>1</span><span>Static</span><span>Primary key, shopify_domain (unique)</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>products</span><span>~500</span><span>Slow (new products added occasionally)</span><span>[shop_id, shopify_id] unique, [shop_id, deleted_at]</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>variants</span><span>~1,500</span><span>Slow (tied to product additions)</span><span>[shop_id, shopify_id] unique, [shop_id, product_id]</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>inventory_snapshots</span><span>~360,000</span><span>Fast (4,000/day, capped at 90 days)</span><span>[shop_id, variant_id, created_at DESC]</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>alerts</span><span>~5,000</span><span>Moderate (depends on stock levels)</span><span>[shop_id, variant_id, created_at], [shop_id, status]</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>suppliers</span><span>~20</span><span>Very slow</span><span>[shop_id] (small table, no additional indexes needed)</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>purchase_orders</span><span>~100</span><span>Slow (AI-generated, weekly)</span><span>[shop_id, supplier_id], [shop_id, status]</span></div>
        <div class="v-table__row"><span>audit_logs</span><span>~10,000</span><span>Moderate (every security event)</span><span>[shop_id, created_at], [action]</span></div>
      </div>

      <h3>Index design philosophy</h3>
      <p>Indexes are the most impactful performance optimization in a database-backed application — a missing index can turn a 1ms query into a 500ms table scan. We follow these principles:</p>

      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Tenant-first composite indexes</span><span class="v-stack__why">Every index that includes <code>shop_id</code> places it as the first column. This ensures the index is useful for tenant-scoped queries (which all of our queries are, thanks to <code>acts_as_tenant</code>). A composite index on <code>[shop_id, created_at]</code> supports both <code>WHERE shop_id = ?</code> and <code>WHERE shop_id = ? AND created_at > ?</code>, but not <code>WHERE created_at > ?</code> alone (which we never need, because all queries are tenant-scoped).</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Covering indexes for hot queries</span><span class="v-stack__why">The inventory stats query (<code>DISTINCT ON (variant_id) ... ORDER BY variant_id, created_at DESC</code>) is the most frequently executed query in the application. The index on <code>[shop_id, variant_id, created_at DESC]</code> covers this query completely — PostgreSQL can satisfy the query entirely from the index without touching the table data (an index-only scan). This reduces the query time from ~250ms (sequential scan) to ~15ms (index-only scan) on a 360,000-row table.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Partial indexes for filtered queries</span><span class="v-stack__why">The <code>.active</code> scope (<code>WHERE deleted_at IS NULL</code>) is used on almost every product query. A partial index <code>CREATE INDEX ON products (shop_id) WHERE deleted_at IS NULL</code> is smaller and faster than a full index because it excludes soft-deleted rows. PostgreSQL recognizes the partial index when the query includes the same <code>WHERE</code> condition.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">No over-indexing</span><span class="v-stack__why">Every index costs: disk space, write performance (inserts and updates must update all indexes), and VACUUM overhead. We do not create indexes "just in case" — every index corresponds to a specific query pattern that appears in our code. The <code>suppliers</code> table has no additional indexes beyond <code>shop_id</code> because it is small (~20 rows per shop) and a sequential scan is faster than an index lookup for tables this small.</span></div>
      </div>

      <h3>Key schema decisions</h3>
      <div class="v-compare">
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">JSONB for shop settings</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--solved">Chose</span>
          <p>Shop-level settings (timezone, default reorder threshold, alert email, LLM provider preference, API keys for custom LLM providers) are stored in a single <code>settings</code> JSONB column on the <code>shops</code> table. This is a departure from the normalized approach of having a separate <code>settings</code> table or individual columns for each setting.</p>
          <p>The JSONB approach offers three advantages. First, adding a new setting requires zero migrations — just start reading/writing a new key in the JSON. For a rapidly evolving application where new settings are added frequently (every feature might need a configuration option), avoiding migrations for each new setting significantly reduces deployment friction. Second, settings with complex structures (like per-variant threshold overrides, which would be an object mapping variant IDs to threshold values) fit naturally in JSON but would require an additional table in a normalized schema. Third, PostgreSQL's JSONB operators allow querying and indexing within the JSON — <code>settings->>'timezone'</code> can be indexed if needed.</p>
          <p>The tradeoffs are real. There are no database-level constraints on individual settings — you cannot add <code>NOT NULL</code> or <code>CHECK</code> constraints to a JSON key. We validate settings at the application level (model validations on the virtual attributes backed by the JSONB column). API keys stored in the JSONB are encrypted by Rails' <code>encrypts</code> on the parent <code>Shop</code> model — but they are encrypted as part of the entire column, not individually. For higher security, sensitive settings (API keys) should be in separate encrypted columns. This is a known tradeoff we accept for the MVP.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">DISTINCT ON for latest snapshots</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--solved">Chose</span>
          <p>PostgreSQL's <code>DISTINCT ON</code> is a non-standard SQL extension that returns the first row for each distinct value of the specified columns, based on the <code>ORDER BY</code> clause. Our critical query: <code>SELECT DISTINCT ON (variant_id) * FROM inventory_snapshots WHERE shop_id = ? ORDER BY variant_id, created_at DESC</code>. This returns the most recent snapshot for each variant in a single query — no subqueries, no window functions, no self-joins.</p>
          <p>The standard SQL approach would be a subquery or CTE: <code>SELECT * FROM inventory_snapshots WHERE (variant_id, created_at) IN (SELECT variant_id, MAX(created_at) FROM inventory_snapshots GROUP BY variant_id)</code>. This is more verbose, harder to read, and often slower because the database must execute the subquery first and then join the results. The <code>ROW_NUMBER()</code> window function approach is another option: <code>SELECT * FROM (SELECT *, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY variant_id ORDER BY created_at DESC) as rn FROM inventory_snapshots) WHERE rn = 1</code>. This works on all databases but is also more complex and typically slower than <code>DISTINCT ON</code>.</p>
          <p>The decision to use <code>DISTINCT ON</code> is a deliberate PostgreSQL lock-in. We accept this because: (1) we have no plan to migrate away from PostgreSQL, (2) the performance benefit is significant (~15ms with <code>DISTINCT ON</code> vs. ~45ms with <code>ROW_NUMBER()</code> on 360,000 rows), and (3) the query reads more naturally (<code>DISTINCT ON</code> expresses the intent directly: "give me one row per variant, the latest one").</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Soft deletes on products</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--solved">Chose</span>
          <p>Products are not hard-deleted from the database when they are archived or removed in Shopify. Instead, they receive a <code>deleted_at</code> timestamp. The <code>.active</code> scope (<code>where(deleted_at: nil)</code>) filters them from all UI queries. This preserves historical relationships — alerts reference products, snapshots reference variants (which reference products), and purchase order line items reference variants. Hard-deleting a product would either cascade-delete all related records (losing history) or orphan foreign keys (leaving dangling references).</p>
          <p>We chose a custom <code>deleted_at</code> column over the <code>paranoia</code> gem (which overrides <code>destroy</code> to set <code>deleted_at</code>) or the <code>discard</code> gem (which provides a <code>.kept</code> scope and <code>.discard</code> method). The reason: both gems add complexity (overriding Active Record's <code>destroy</code> method, adding default scopes that can be surprising) for a feature we implement with one column, one scope, and one line of code in the Persister service. The explicit approach is simpler and has no surprising behavior — you always know whether you are querying active or all products because you explicitly include or omit the <code>.active</code> scope.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">JSONB columns vs. normalized tables for variant metadata</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--chose-normalized">Chose normalized</span>
          <p>We considered using JSONB columns for variant metadata (like storing all inventory quantities as <code>{ available: 50, on_hand: 55, committed: 5, incoming: 10 }</code> instead of separate integer columns). This would simplify the schema and make it easy to add new quantity types without migrations.</p>
          <p>We chose separate integer columns because: (1) database-level constraints (<code>CHECK (available >= 0)</code>) can validate individual values — JSONB values cannot have per-key constraints, (2) integer columns are faster for aggregation queries (<code>SUM(available)</code> is a simple column sum, while <code>SUM((data->>'available')::integer)</code> requires JSON parsing per row), (3) the set of inventory quantities is fixed by Shopify's API — we will not need to add new quantity types without a corresponding Shopify API change. The rule of thumb: use JSONB for dynamic, schema-less data (settings, preferences, metadata that varies per record). Use typed columns for structured, consistent data that you query and aggregate.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Query optimization examples</h3>

      <h4>Dashboard stats query</h4>
      <div class="v-code">
        <code>-- Get stock status counts using latest snapshot per variant</code>
        <code>SELECT</code>
        <code>  COUNT(*) AS total_variants,</code>
        <code>  COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE available > threshold) AS healthy,</code>
        <code>  COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE available > 0 AND available <= threshold) AS low_stock,</code>
        <code>  COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE available <= 0) AS out_of_stock</code>
        <code>FROM (</code>
        <code>  SELECT DISTINCT ON (s.variant_id)</code>
        <code>    s.available, v.reorder_threshold AS threshold</code>
        <code>  FROM inventory_snapshots s</code>
        <code>  JOIN variants v ON v.id = s.variant_id</code>
        <code>  WHERE s.shop_id = $1</code>
        <code>  ORDER BY s.variant_id, s.created_at DESC</code>
        <code>) latest_snapshots;</code>
      </div>

      <p>This query runs in approximately 15-25ms on a 360,000-row snapshots table (1,000 variants x 360 snapshots each). The <code>DISTINCT ON</code> uses the <code>[shop_id, variant_id, created_at DESC]</code> index for an index-only scan. The <code>FILTER</code> clauses (PostgreSQL-specific) compute all three counts in a single pass, avoiding multiple queries or <code>CASE WHEN</code> expressions.</p>

      <h3>Migration strategy</h3>
      <p>Every schema change goes through a Rails migration. Migrations must be reversible (include a <code>down</code> method or use <code>change</code> with reversible operations). We follow these principles:</p>

      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Small migrations</span><span class="v-stack__why">Each migration does one thing: add a column, create an index, create a table. Bundling multiple operations in one migration makes rollbacks partial and risky.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Zero-downtime compatibility</span><span class="v-stack__why">Column additions use <code>add_column</code> (never <code>change_column</code> which locks the table). New columns are nullable or have defaults. We never rename columns (use a new column + data migration + remove old column in three separate migrations). Indexes are created with <code>algorithm: :concurrently</code> to avoid table locks.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Data migrations in code</span><span class="v-stack__why">Schema migrations only change the schema. Data transformations (backfilling a new column, migrating data from one format to another) are done in Rake tasks or one-off jobs, not in migrations. This keeps migrations fast and idempotent (running <code>db:migrate</code> should take seconds, not minutes).</span></div>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Snapshot storage scaling analysis</span>
        <p>With 1,000 variants and 4 snapshots per day (one per 4-hour sync), that is 4,000 rows per day per shop, or approximately 1.4 million rows per year per shop. The SnapshotCleanupJob deletes rows older than 90 days, capping the table at approximately 360,000 rows per shop. Each snapshot row is approximately 100 bytes (8 bytes each for id, shop_id, variant_id, available, on_hand, committed, incoming, created_at, plus overhead). At 360,000 rows, the table consumes approximately 36MB per shop, plus approximately 20MB for indexes. With 1,000 shops, the table would be approximately 56GB — well within PostgreSQL's comfort zone but large enough to require attention to index design and query optimization.</p>
        <p>If we reach this scale, we would consider: (1) <strong>table partitioning</strong> by month (<code>CREATE TABLE inventory_snapshots PARTITION BY RANGE (created_at)</code>) — PostgreSQL can prune partitions during queries, avoiding scanning old data, and the cleanup job can simply drop old partitions instead of deleting individual rows. (2) <strong>TimescaleDB</strong>, a PostgreSQL extension for time-series data that provides automatic partitioning (hypertables), time-based aggregation functions, and compression for historical data. (3) <strong>Archival to cold storage</strong> — move snapshots older than 30 days to a compressed archive table with reduced indexes, keeping the hot table small and fast.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">JSONB gotcha: querying nested values</span>
        <p>Querying JSONB columns requires specific operator syntax: <code>settings->>'timezone'</code> returns the value as text, <code>settings->'timezone'</code> returns it as JSONB. The <code>->></code> text operator is needed for comparisons (<code>WHERE settings->>'timezone' = 'America/New_York'</code>). A common mistake is using <code>-></code> (returns JSONB) in a text comparison, which silently returns no results because <code>'"America/New_York"'::jsonb != 'America/New_York'::text</code> (the JSONB value includes quotes). We standardize on <code>->></code> for all setting queries and validate at the application level to avoid this database-level footgun.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Future direction</span>
        <p>Add table partitioning for <code>inventory_snapshots</code> when the table exceeds 10 million rows across all tenants. Evaluate TimescaleDB for time-series features (continuous aggregates for pre-computed trend data, compression for historical snapshots). Add <code>pg_stat_statements</code> monitoring in production to identify slow queries and missing indexes. Consider adding PostgreSQL Row-Level Security policies as an additional layer of tenant isolation defense. Implement <code>EXPLAIN ANALYZE</code> logging for queries exceeding 100ms to catch performance regressions early.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- ═══════ TAB: Future ═══════ -->
    <article class="v-tab" id="tab-future">
      <span class="v-num">12</span>
      <h2>Future Roadmap</h2>
      <div class="v-tags"><span class="v-tag">Roadmap</span><span class="v-tag">v2</span><span class="v-tag">v3</span></div>

      <h3>Planned features — Tier 1 (next 2 weeks)</h3>
      <p>These features build on the existing infrastructure and require no new architectural components. They are ordered by dependency and impact.</p>

      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Demo Mode</span><span class="v-stack__why">A toggle in the settings that fills the dashboard with 500+ realistic products, variants, snapshots, suppliers, and alerts for demonstrations and screenshots. Architecture: a Rake task or service class that generates seed data using FactoryBot or a custom generator. The data is scoped to a dedicated "demo shop" that is created on toggle-on and destroyed on toggle-off. This is the highest-priority feature because it enables demonstrating all other features without requiring a real Shopify store with inventory.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Predictive Stockouts</span><span class="v-stack__why">The core value proposition upgrade. Uses weighted moving averages from snapshot data to predict when each variant will reach zero stock. Algorithm: (1) query the last 14 days of snapshots for each variant, (2) calculate daily consumption as the difference between consecutive snapshots, (3) apply exponential weighting (recent days weighted higher), (4) divide current stock by weighted average daily consumption. Output: "Snowboard Ice will be out of stock in approximately 5.2 days at current sell-through rate." Dependencies: existing snapshot infrastructure, new <code>predicted_stockout_date</code> column on variants, new agent tool <code>get_stockout_predictions</code>. Estimated effort: 3-4 days across 2 PRs (algorithm service + agent tool integration).</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">One-Click Reorder</span><span class="v-stack__why">Builds on predictions and the existing <code>draft_purchase_order</code> agent tool. Flow: (1) dashboard shows variants approaching stockout, (2) merchant clicks "Generate PO", (3) AI agent drafts a purchase order for the relevant supplier with calculated quantities, (4) merchant previews the PO in an overlay, (5) merchant clicks "Send to Supplier", (6) the PO is emailed to the supplier's contact address. Dependencies: predictive stockouts (for proactive PO generation), email sending (SendGrid integration, already configured), PO email template. Estimated effort: 4-5 days across 3 PRs (PO preview UI + email template + send flow).</span></div>
      </div>

      <h3>Planned features — Tier 2 (weeks 3-4)</h3>
      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Live Agent Stream</span><span class="v-stack__why">Watch the AI agent think in real-time. Architecture: (1) when the merchant clicks "Run Analysis", a Sidekiq job starts the agent loop, (2) at each step (tool call, tool result, text generation), the job publishes an event to a Redis pub/sub channel keyed by shop_id, (3) a streaming controller (<code>AgentStreamController</code>) subscribes to the channel and forwards events to the browser via Server-Sent Events (SSE), (4) HTMX's <code>sse</code> extension renders each event as it arrives. The merchant sees: "Checking inventory... Found 12 low-stock items... Checking recent alerts... 8 already alerted... Sending 4 new alerts... Drafting purchase order for Acme Supplies..." This transforms the agent from a black box to a transparent assistant. Dependencies: Redis pub/sub (already available), SSE support in Rails (built-in via <code>ActionController::Live</code>), HTMX sse extension (available via CDN). Estimated effort: 3-4 days across 2 PRs (backend streaming + frontend rendering). Risk: SSE connections hold a thread open for the duration of the stream — with 5 Sidekiq threads, only 5 concurrent streams are possible. Mitigation: use a separate Puma thread pool for streaming requests, or switch to ActionCable (WebSocket-based) if concurrent stream count exceeds available threads.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Customer DNA Profiles</span><span class="v-stack__why">Purchase history analysis and customer segmentation using order data from Shopify's API. For each customer: calculate total orders, total spend, average order value, product category preferences, purchase frequency, and estimated lifetime value. Segment customers into cohorts (new, returning, VIP, churning) based on RFM (Recency, Frequency, Monetary) analysis. This data feeds into the AI agent's analysis — the agent can correlate low-stock items with VIP customer preferences to prioritize reordering. Dependencies: <code>read_customers</code> and <code>read_orders</code> OAuth scopes (already requested), new <code>customer_profiles</code> table, new sync pipeline stage for order data. Estimated effort: 5-7 days across 4 PRs (data model + sync + analysis service + agent integration). Risk: order data can be large — a store with 10,000 orders requires significant processing. Mitigation: process orders incrementally (only new orders since last sync) using Shopify's <code>created_at_min</code> filter.</span></div>
      </div>

      <h3>Planned features — Tier 3 (month 2+)</h3>
      <div class="v-stack">
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Multi-Location Inventory</span><span class="v-stack__why">Per-warehouse stock levels instead of aggregated totals. Requires: (1) <code>read_locations</code> OAuth scope, (2) <code>location_id</code> column on <code>inventory_snapshots</code>, (3) location-specific reorder thresholds, (4) location picker in the dashboard UI, (5) location-scoped alerts ("Warehouse A is out of Snowboard Ice, but Warehouse B has 50 units"). This is a significant schema and UI change that affects every layer of the application. Estimated effort: 2 weeks across 5 PRs.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Supplier Portal</span><span class="v-stack__why">A separate, unauthenticated interface where suppliers can view purchase orders, confirm receipt, and update delivery estimates. No Shopify OAuth — suppliers access via a unique, time-limited link emailed to their contact address. Architecture: a new controller with token-based authentication (generate a random token per PO, include in the email link, expire after 7 days). The supplier sees the PO details and can update the status (confirmed, shipped, delivered). This closes the reorder loop — currently POs are emailed but there is no feedback mechanism for supplier confirmation.</span></div>
        <div class="v-stack__item"><span class="v-stack__name">Shopify Flow Integration</span><span class="v-stack__why">Publish StockPilot events as Shopify Flow triggers, allowing merchants to build custom automations. Example: "When StockPilot detects a low-stock item → tag the product in Shopify → notify the team in Slack." This requires implementing Shopify's Flow connector API, which involves registering trigger schemas and publishing events via webhook. Significant Shopify App Store value — Flow integrations are highlighted in app listings.</span></div>
      </div>

      <h3>Architecture changes needed</h3>
      <div class="v-compare">
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">App Bridge JWT (required for App Store)</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--planned">Required — blocking for launch</span>
          <p>Replace cookie-based sessions with Shopify App Bridge session tokens. This is <strong>mandatory</strong> for Shopify App Store approval — Shopify rejects apps that do not use App Bridge for authentication in embedded mode. Every frontend request will include a JWT signed by Shopify, validated server-side. The JWT contains the shop domain, staff member ID, and expiration timestamp.</p>
          <p>Implementation plan: (1) add the App Bridge JavaScript SDK to the application layout via Shopify's CDN, (2) write a small JavaScript module (~30 lines) that fetches a session token from App Bridge and attaches it to HTMX requests via the <code>hx-headers</code> attribute, (3) add a <code>verify_session_token</code> before_action that decodes the JWT, verifies the signature using Shopify's public key, checks expiration, and extracts the shop domain, (4) replace the current cookie-based <code>require_login</code> with the JWT-based authentication, (5) remove the cookie session configuration. Estimated effort: 2-3 days. Risk: HTMX does not natively support refreshing headers between requests — if the JWT expires mid-session, subsequent requests will fail. Mitigation: intercept HTMX's <code>htmx:configRequest</code> event to refresh the token before each request.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Pundit authorization</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--planned">Planned — important for multi-user shops</span>
          <p>Resource-level authorization beyond tenant isolation. Currently, any authenticated user from a shop can perform any action — view all data, modify settings, approve purchase orders, trigger AI analysis, manage suppliers. For single-owner shops, this is fine. For shops with multiple staff members (common in mid-market), role-based access control is important: who can approve purchase orders? Who can modify alert thresholds? Who can change the LLM provider and potentially incur different costs?</p>
          <p>Pundit is the standard Ruby authorization library. It uses policy classes (<code>PurchaseOrderPolicy</code>) with predicate methods (<code>def approve?</code>) that return true or false based on the user's role and the resource's state. Controllers call <code>authorize @purchase_order</code> before performing the action. The architecture is simple, testable, and does not add global state — each policy class is a plain Ruby object that receives the user and the record.</p>
          <p>Dependencies: a <code>role</code> column on the shop-user association (or a separate <code>staff_members</code> table if Shopify provides staff member data via the API). Shopify's App Bridge provides the staff member ID in the session token — we could use this to look up the user's role. Estimated effort: 3-4 days across 2 PRs (Pundit setup + policies for existing resources).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">ActionCable or Turbo Streams</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--planned">Planned for streaming features</span>
          <p>Live agent streaming needs a persistent connection between the server and the browser. We plan to implement raw SSE first (simpler architecture, no WebSocket infrastructure needed). SSE uses a standard HTTP connection that the server keeps open, pushing events as they occur. The client receives events via the <code>EventSource</code> API (or HTMX's <code>sse</code> extension).</p>
          <p>If we need bidirectional communication (collaborative features, real-time inventory updates from multiple users viewing the same dashboard), we would upgrade to ActionCable with Redis adapter. ActionCable provides WebSocket support with Rails conventions: channels, subscribers, and broadcasts. The Redis adapter enables multi-server deployment (messages are relayed via Redis pub/sub so all servers receive broadcasts). The complexity cost is higher — WebSocket connections require a separate connection manager, authentication is handled differently than HTTP requests, and connection state management adds code. We defer this until we have a concrete bidirectional communication requirement.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="v-compare__row">
          <span class="v-compare__alt">Separate Redis instances</span>
          <span class="v-compare__verdict v-compare__verdict--planned">Planned for production</span>
          <p>Split the single Redis instance into two: one for caching (LRU eviction) and one for Sidekiq (noeviction). This is the most important infrastructure change for production reliability. A single Redis instance with LRU eviction can silently drop Sidekiq jobs when memory is full — an unacceptable failure mode for a system where dropped jobs mean missed inventory alerts. The change is straightforward: two Redis URLs in environment variables, two configurations in Rails initializers, two monitoring targets in observability. Estimated effort: 1 day including testing and documentation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Build order and dependencies</span>
        <p><strong>Week 1:</strong> Demo Mode (enables demoing all features without real data) → App Bridge JWT (unblocks App Store submission). <strong>Week 2:</strong> Predictive Stockouts (core value prop, uses existing snapshot data) → One-Click Reorder (builds on predictions + existing PO drafting). <strong>Week 3:</strong> Live Agent Stream (polish, uses existing Redis pub/sub) → Customer DNA Profiles (new data pipeline). <strong>Week 4:</strong> Pundit Authorization (security hardening) → Separate Redis (infrastructure reliability). <strong>Month 2+:</strong> Multi-Location Inventory → Supplier Portal → Shopify Flow Integration. Total estimated effort for Tier 1 + Tier 2: approximately 3 weeks of focused development. The critical path runs through App Bridge JWT (blocks App Store) and Demo Mode (blocks effective demonstrations and investor presentations).</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Risks and mitigations</span>
        <p><strong>Risk 1: App Bridge JWT migration breaks existing sessions.</strong> Mitigation: implement both auth methods simultaneously (cookie + JWT) behind a feature flag, then switch to JWT-only after testing. <strong>Risk 2: Predictive stockout algorithm is inaccurate for seasonal products.</strong> Mitigation: weight recent data heavily (exponential moving average), and clearly label predictions as estimates with confidence ranges. <strong>Risk 3: Live agent streaming overwhelms Puma threads.</strong> Mitigation: limit concurrent streams per shop (max 2), implement stream timeout (auto-close after 60 seconds), and monitor thread utilization. <strong>Risk 4: Customer DNA processing is slow for large stores.</strong> Mitigation: process orders incrementally (only new orders since last sync), use batch processing with <code>find_each</code>, and set a per-shop processing time limit.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="v-callout">
        <span class="v-callout__label">Scaling considerations</span>
        <p>The current architecture comfortably supports approximately 500 shops with a single Rails process, a single Sidekiq process (5 threads), and a single PostgreSQL instance. Beyond that scale: (1) add horizontal scaling for Rails (multiple Puma workers behind a load balancer — straightforward with session tokens since there is no server-side session state), (2) add horizontal scaling for Sidekiq (multiple Sidekiq processes, possibly on separate machines), (3) add read replicas for PostgreSQL (route dashboard queries to replicas, write operations to the primary), (4) split Redis as described above. The monolith architecture makes horizontal scaling simpler than microservices — you deploy more instances of the same application, not more instances of different services. The main constraint is the PostgreSQL connection pool — with 500 shops and concurrent requests, connection pooling via PgBouncer becomes necessary.</p>
      </div>
